page.title: 10Ecology
page.content: Large parts of our D-block are covered with swamp, heath-land, and wood-land. There are many wild deer, foxes, rabbits and snakes. This area is particularly famous for the Natterjack Toad. This toad has become so rare that it is now an endangered species. Several of the roads have signs with a picture of a toad to warn motorists. The natterjack toad lives in sandy places and buries itself during the day. It does not hop like a frog, but walks about on all four legs.It is green in colour and has warts all over its back. There are many different types of bird living in the woods. There are other kinds that live in the open farmland.There are both coniferous and deciduous trees. The soil is rather acid in places so rhododendrons grow well.
